review_topics: quick and peppy systeminput: So today my boyfriend and I visited our local Best Buy to finally get him his first gaming laptop! He had done his research and decided on the ASUS ROG GL551JW-DS74
we got to the store and played with the display model for a little while and were really happy with it so we decided to take the plunge. So
it was super easy to set up and we went to go play the first game
the laptop seemed to be able to handle high graphics
but during gameplay he noticed that the laptop was freezing for a couple of seconds randomly
so he turned down the graphics to medium
and after that he got "DirectX function "GetDeviceRemovedReason" failed with DXGI_ERROR_DEVICE_HUNG." He read a few forums and tried every possible fix that he could find
so after about 3 hours of troubleshooting we gave up for the night and decided to try again in the morning. When we woke up

this time he started up Dragon Age and then ran a stress test on the GPU and the laptop remained stable so we thought that maybe it was just a one time thing? He went back to playing and within an hour
the same thing happened. This time he tried updating the drivers
but that didn`t work. He was so frustrated so I decided to do some troubleshooting of my own

I hooked up my laptop and a monitor to his and noticed that when the freezing occurred the framerate on both screens would drop. I then continued to google around and came across a forum post about disabling the NVIDIA Optimus technology. The post stated that his laptop had been freezing during gameplay due to Optimus and after disabling it
his laptop ran perfectly. And guess what? That was the problem this whole time. So
the game played smoothly with the graphics turned up to high once again
with no freezing or crashing. Hooray!output: ASUS ROG GL551JW-DS74
NVIDIA Optimus technologyinput: Still good for 2015
as long as one is willing to do a bit of tweaking to run the games we play.output: good for 2015

review_topics: screen not workinginput: The N61JQ-X1 uses Intel's Turbo Boost technology to automatically overclock the i7-2630QM processor from its base speed of 2GHz to 2.9GHz when needed
giving it a significant performance boost. The i7-2630QM is a quad-core processor with Hyper-Threading

which means it can process up to eight threads simultaneously. This makes it ideal for multitasking and running demanding applications. The N61JQ-X1's 8GB of DDR3 memory provides plenty of headroom for running multiple programs and large files. The memory is upgradeable to 16GB if needed. The N61JQ-X1's 1TB hard drive provides ample storage space for your programs
and media. The hard drive is a 7200RPM drive
which means it is faster than most other laptop hard drives. The N61JQ-X1's 15.6-inch LED backlit display has a resolution of 1366x768 pixels. The display is bright and clear

and it provides good viewing angles. The N61JQ-X1's graphics card is the NVIDIA GeForce GT 540M. The GT 540M is a mid-range graphics card that is capable of playing most games at medium to high settings. The N61JQ-X1's battery life is average. The battery lasts for about 4 hours on a single charge. The N61JQ-X1 is a well-rounded laptop that is ideal for multitasking
and playing games. It is a good value for the price.output: Intel's Turbo Boost technology

title: Wonderful
review_topics: I have been using this notebook regularly for the past 9 years. I originally purchased the device for its size and portability
but found that it didn't really have the horsepower to keep up with Windows 7 (Starter Edition). After several months
I chose to upgrade the system RAM from 1GB to 2GB
but it was still pretty laggy

especially when surfing the web. After several years of so-so performance I installed Linux Mint 17 (now 18) on the machine and boy what a difference that made. The netbook went from being a machine that I kept in the bag most of the time to becoming my daily driver. The sluggish
laggy performance with Windows 7 was replaced with snappy
in conjunction with the small form factor

made the netbook an ideal on-the-go device. I can safely say 9 years after my original purchase that the machine is significantly faster today running Linux Mint than it was when brand new running Windows 7 Starter. My wife and I own a multi-million dollar IT services company

and this netbook has been serving as my primary business  laptop   for the past 5 years. At this juncture I wouldn't trade my old netbook for a brand new device... its become like an old trusted friend.
